<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com – The pound extended losses against the U.S. dollar Wednesday, after official data showed that U.S. core inflation posted its largest monthly gain in nearly three years last month.GBP/USD hit 1.6227 during early U.S. trade, the pair’s lowest since Monday; the pair subsequently consolidated at 1.6251, dropping 0.72%.Cable was likely to find short-term support at 1.6130, the low of May 25 and resistance at 1.6382, the days high.Earlier in the day, the U.S. Labor Department said consumer prices rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.2% in May, after a 0.4% increase the previous month. Core inflation, which excludes volatile energy and food costs, rose by 0.3% in May, the biggest jump since July 2008, after rising by 0.2% in April. Economists had forecast a 0.1% rise in overall prices, and a 0.2% gain for core inflation.The report said the rise in underlying inflation was mainly driven by price increases for clothing, housing, new vehicles and recreation. Meanwhile, the pound was up against the euro, with EUR/GBP shedding 0.30% to hit 0.8794.Also Wednesday, official data showed that the number of people in the U.K. claiming unemployment benefits rose at the fastest pace in almost two years last month.The U.K. Office for National Statistics said the claimant count rose by a seasonally adjusted 19,600 in May, far more than the expected 6,500 forecast gain.The report said the unemployment rate held steady in April at 7.7%, in line with expectations but a separate report showed that the average earnings index rose less-than-expected in April.             ]]></raw>
